difficult from traditional database sort of thinking ways.

00:16:57.400 --> 00:17:02.599
But we really think that in order to make an impact in how people think about data,

00:17:02.599 --> 00:17:04.900
which is kind of what we're trying to do here,

00:17:04.900 --> 00:17:06.699
we really need to give people the tools,

00:17:06.699 --> 00:17:10.699
the state-of-the-art tools to work with big data sets.

00:17:10.699 --> 00:17:14.099
And we can't really, you know, make this just happen for one company

00:17:14.099 --> 00:17:15.900
or for the customers of one company.

00:17:15.900 --> 00:17:19.099
We have to really make this work for everyone.

00:17:19.099 --> 00:17:21.199
The world is kind of lacking DuckDB.

00:17:21.199 --> 00:17:23.699
So here's a plot of the GitHub stars.

00:17:23.699 --> 00:17:27.699
It's a very, it's a crap metric. Mostly VCs care about this.

00:17:27.699 --> 00:17:31.500
But it's interesting to see how this is going on.

00:17:31.500 --> 00:17:36.599
So we really have an exponential growth in the adoption of DuckDB.

00:17:36.599 --> 00:17:40.000
We're really, really grateful about it.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:45.599
We eventually spun off from the Research Institute into a company called DuckDB Labs

00:17:45.599 --> 00:17:50.099
because every open source project needs to fund itself somehow.

00:17:50.099 --> 00:17:52.599
You can fund the open source project by working for another company

00:17:52.599 --> 00:17:57.000
and then doing nights and weekends, but I can't really do that.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.199
You can sell your soul to VCs

00:17:59.199 --> 00:18:02.699
and then basically, you know, continue until the party stops

00:18:02.699 --> 00:18:06.199
and somebody has to change a license.

00:18:06.199 --> 00:18:11.400
But DuckDB itself is, yeah, backed by DuckDB Labs,

00:18:11.400 --> 00:18:16.500
which is a company that provides support and consulting contracts around DuckDB,

00:18:16.500 --> 00:18:20.599
but actually is not the owner of the software itself, which is in a non-profit.

00:18:20.599 --> 00:18:25.699
So this is really a unique setup that we don't have, you know,

00:18:25.699 --> 00:18:30.900
we see interest in the company, but it's a long-term effort backed by an independent foundation

00:18:30.900 --> 00:18:33.699
just to make sure that this thing keeps being available.

00:18:33.699 --> 00:18:38.500
So even we have trouble, are going to have trouble sort of rug pulling this.

00:18:38.500 --> 00:18:42.099
And DuckDB loves R. Hey!

00:18:42.099 --> 00:18:46.199
As I said, the motivation to build DuckDB came from interactions with the R community.

00:18:46.199 --> 00:18:50.199
I actually spoke about DuckDB for the first time at Kirill's meetup.

00:18:50.199 --> 00:18:55.400
Where's Kirill? In Zurich in summer of 2019.

00:18:55.400 --> 00:18:57.400
That was a long time ago.

00:18:57.400 --> 00:19:01.300
And because it's in process, we can actually do some pretty amazing things within R.

00:19:01.300 --> 00:19:07.300
So for example, DuckDB running inside the R process can directly read any data frame

00:19:07.300 --> 00:19:10.800
that you have inside the R process as if it were a table.

00:19:10.800 --> 00:19:14.400
There's no, you know, we don't have to first convert this to anything or like, no, no, no.

00:19:14.400 --> 00:19:18.199
If a data frame exists inside your R process, we can run queries on it.

00:19:18.199 --> 00:19:23.000
And we can also take the query results that we produce from DuckDB

00:19:23.000 --> 00:19:25.000
and convert them directly into data frames.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.500
And some systems out there have kind of also functionally like this,

00:19:28.500 --> 00:19:30.900
but it tends to be insanely slow.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:33.599
We can do this very quickly because we're sitting in the same process space.

00:19:33.599 --> 00:19:39.000
We don't have to do any serialization or any of that sort.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:44.199
We also love Python. So it's the biggest API actually by downloads per month.

00:19:44.199 --> 00:19:47.400
It's like six million downloads per month. It's pretty ridiculous.

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:50.400
And we can do also the same trick with pandas data frames.

00:19:50.400 --> 00:19:54.900
So if you run DuckDB in a Python process and you have a pandas data frame sitting there,

00:19:54.900 --> 00:19:57.800
we can also treat it as a table and read it.

00:19:57.800 --> 00:20:00.000
We can also produce results again as pandas data frames

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:04.199
because that allows us to integrate with downstream libraries.

00:20:04.199 --> 00:20:11.000
And because many data sets or many tools are starting to support Apache Arrow as intermediates,

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:13.300
we can also do the same trick for R and Python.

00:20:13.300 --> 00:20:18.099
If the data happens to be Arrow, we can read and write from it directly.

00:20:18.099 --> 00:20:20.599
Even streaming. So we don't actually have to copy things.

00:20:20.599 --> 00:20:23.300
It's just streaming into Arrow, streaming from Arrow.

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:27.400
That works all really well. So that's DuckDB in a nutshell.

00:20:27.400 --> 00:20:32.900
Let's revisit the statement. Slower and more frustrating.

00:20:32.900 --> 00:20:37.300
I'm going to go back to the running example in a bit, our wonderful CSV file.

00:20:37.300 --> 00:20:43.900
First, I want to say we actually wrote a research paper on CSV parsing.

00:20:43.900 --> 00:20:47.099
Because it turns out that this is such an annoying issue

00:20:47.099 --> 00:20:50.900
that you can actually write a computer science research paper on it.

00:20:50.900 --> 00:20:53.800
I think we may have been the first ones that have done this.

00:20:53.800 --> 00:20:55.300
There's some happened afterwards.

00:20:55.300 --> 00:21:00.400
But as a result, we actually have one of the best CSV readers out there in DuckDB

00:21:00.400 --> 00:21:06.900
because we realize that your analysis starts with getting data from somewhere else, right?

00:21:06.900 --> 00:21:10.099
You're not going to sit down and type everything into DuckDB.

00:21:10.099 --> 00:21:11.400
You're going to use something else.

00:21:11.400 --> 00:21:15.400
And so we brought this research paper and we took the ideas from the research paper

00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:19.500
and put them into DuckDB. A shout out to Pedro from our team

00:21:19.500 --> 00:21:21.500
who worked incredibly hard on this.

00:21:21.500 --> 00:21:25.500
And we can actually read most files out there without human interaction.

00:21:25.500 --> 00:21:31.699
So, for example, in DuckDB, you can just type from data so-and-so, so-and-so, right?

00:21:31.699 --> 00:21:35.400
And this is technically a SQL query.

00:21:35.400 --> 00:21:39.599
We can treat table, if you don't, if this is using a table name,

00:21:39.599 --> 00:21:41.199
using the file as a table name.

00:21:41.199 --> 00:21:44.300
And we have this logic that says if the table isn't there and there's a file with the same name,

00:21:44.300 --> 00:21:45.500
well, probably we should read this file.

00:21:45.500 --> 00:21:47.599
And if it ends with CSV, it's probably a CSV file.

00:21:47.599 --> 00:21:50.900
So we do a lot of sort of guessing just to reduce the frustration.

00:21:50.900 --> 00:21:54.599
And you will see that it has indeed read this file correctly

00:21:54.599 --> 00:21:58.099
with all the column types and so on and so forth.

00:21:58.099 --> 00:21:59.500
And it can show this.

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:03.699
We also have some cool features in DuckDB like summarize, right?

00:22:03.699 --> 00:22:07.199
So we have some features that are trying to make your life as an analyst easier,

00:22:07.300 --> 00:22:09.900
even if the data set is huge.

00:22:09.900 --> 00:22:15.300
So to summarize is pretty cool, actually, because you just say summarize any query, really,

00:22:15.300 --> 00:22:19.800
and we will compute a ton of summary statistics very efficiently on this file.

00:22:19.800 --> 00:22:22.400
So this is a couple of million row files.

00:22:22.400 --> 00:22:24.900
And in very few, a very short amount of time,

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:28.000
we will give you like the minimum, the maximum, the approximate, unique,

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:30.599
the average, the standard deviation, the quantiles, and non-allocals,

00:22:30.599 --> 00:22:35.599
and a lot of stuff for all the columns in the file, right?

00:22:35.599 --> 00:22:37.199
And this is a single pass thing.

00:22:37.199 --> 00:22:39.900
So we read through the file once using our efficient implementation.

00:22:39.900 --> 00:22:43.400
We give you a good overview of what's in the file.

00:22:43.400 --> 00:22:46.000
And I said that we're not going to care too much about performance,

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:51.400
but I couldn't resist but saying despite this being one of the most flexible CSV readers out there,

00:22:51.400 --> 00:22:54.800
it also is the fastest, okay? So this is cool.

00:22:54.800 --> 00:23:00.400
So now we've got the frustration of running queries a bit out of the,

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:04.900
of, sorry, of reading CSV files kind of sorted. Good.

00:23:04.900 --> 00:23:09.199
But let's do a bit more complex queries, okay?

00:23:09.199 --> 00:23:10.699
I didn't get to this part with Postgres

00:23:10.699 --> 00:23:14.099
because it was too frustrated to kind of continue at some point.

00:23:14.099 --> 00:23:16.000
But we're actually not here to read CSV files.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:19.699
We're here to answer analysis questions.

00:23:19.699 --> 00:23:23.000
So here I have a totally made-up analysis questions.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:28.500
So given this data set, give me the number of non-Europeans between 20 and 40

00:23:28.500 --> 00:23:32.300
that live in Auckland area from the 2018 census and group that by sex.

00:23:32.300 --> 00:23:38.699
Okay. So if now somebody has to translate it into a SQL query,

00:23:38.699 --> 00:23:41.199
if you have generative AI, maybe you can try,

00:23:41.199 --> 00:23:44.300
but I have just written down the SQL query.

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.800
And it's basically, you can see it's not, it's nothing dramatic.

00:23:47.800 --> 00:23:50.699
It's doing a bunch of things where we like joined all these data sets together

00:23:50.699 --> 00:23:54.000
because the columns are actually codes and not actually values,

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:57.900
except for the count, which is sometimes a value, but sometimes also C.

00:23:57.900 --> 00:24:01.000
And it is a bunch of cleanups because the statistics people in New Zealand

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:04.300
somehow include totals in all the dimensions

00:24:04.300 --> 00:24:07.199
and there's rows in the main data that are aggregates of either other.

00:24:07.199 --> 00:24:10.099
And we obviously don't want that in a tidy data set.

00:24:10.099 --> 00:24:16.099
But if you just ignore all this, we can run this fairly complex query

00:24:16.099 --> 00:24:18.900
and it completes in one second.

00:24:18.900 --> 00:24:24.099
That's kind of weird, right? Because, oops, sorry, I wanted to go here.

00:24:24.099 --> 00:24:28.300
It's kind of weird because I just told you it took 1.1 second to read this file, right?

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:34.699
How can you, oops, sorry, how can you run this complicated query over all the files,

00:24:34.699 --> 00:24:37.300
joining them all together, doing aggregation along multiple things,

00:24:37.300 --> 00:24:39.900
doing a bunch of projections, filters and all that in one second?

00:24:39.900 --> 00:24:41.900
Well, again, magic.

00:24:41.900 --> 00:24:44.699
And what the reason is actually what DuckDB does,

00:24:44.699 --> 00:24:49.400
it takes the query and turns it into this query plan,

00:24:49.400 --> 00:24:53.000
which we call a query plan, which is kind of a high-level concept

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:55.300
of how the query should be executed.

00:24:55.300 --> 00:24:58.500
And this is optimized and then executed in parallel.

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:01.199
So the filters, for example, they move all the way down.

00:25:01.199 --> 00:25:07.000
So we remove data from the path of the data for the query as early as possible.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:10.699
We prune all the columns that we don't need as early as possible.

00:25:10.699 --> 00:25:15.599
And it's a streaming engine, which means we don't actually have to materialize any of this in memory.

00:25:15.599 --> 00:25:18.500
And yeah, so it's really efficient.

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:24.099
But then I realized that not everybody loves SQL.

00:25:24.199 --> 00:25:25.199
I realized this.

00:25:25.199 --> 00:25:29.199
So let's explore alternatives, shall we say.

00:25:29.199 --> 00:25:32.000
So obviously we can also do this in dplyr,

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:36.300
which I think is much nicer to write and to sort of reason about.

00:25:36.300 --> 00:25:38.699
So I've written down the exact same thing in dplyr,

00:25:38.699 --> 00:25:42.099
and I've actually checked whether the results are equivalent, and they are.

00:25:42.099 --> 00:25:46.199
So this is the same kind of thing where we basically make this

00:25:46.199 --> 00:25:49.300
sort of joined together data set with all these joins and the mutations and filters.

00:25:49.300 --> 00:25:52.699
And then the very bottom we have our final analysis on this

00:25:52.699 --> 00:25:55.199
free current data set, and it takes 15 seconds.

00:25:55.199 --> 00:25:58.900
It's not so terrible, but this is exactly why on this reasonably sized data set,

00:25:58.900 --> 00:26:01.199
we do see a significant difference in speed,

00:26:01.199 --> 00:26:05.400
just because we don't have a sort of holistic optimization happening here.

00:26:05.400 --> 00:26:10.199
dplyr is eagerly executing everything as it does.

00:26:10.199 --> 00:26:12.500
So enter duckplyr.

00:26:12.500 --> 00:26:20.400
So we've been actually working with Posit to create sort of a hybrid mutant of dplyr and duckdb.

00:26:20.400 --> 00:26:22.199
And the result is duckplyr.

00:26:22.199 --> 00:26:26.500
I mean, you have maybe seen the stickers I've put a bunch outside.

00:26:26.500 --> 00:26:30.099
So massive thanks again to Kirill for his hard work on this.

00:26:30.099 --> 00:26:33.500
It's dplyr, just re-engined with duckdb.

00:26:33.500 --> 00:26:37.199
And you have the exact same syntax, so the syntax is exactly the same.

00:26:37.199 --> 00:26:41.599
And this, from the CSVs, directly finishes in 1.5 seconds.

00:26:41.599 --> 00:26:47.699
So that is because we have done this high-level reasoning about how this query should be executed

00:26:47.699 --> 00:26:51.500
and directly on the CSV files, and we can do this 10 times faster.

00:26:51.500 --> 00:26:55.000
From parquet files, it's actually half that, so more on that later.

00:26:55.000 --> 00:26:59.900
If you run the same query from the data frames that are already loaded into our session,

00:26:59.900 --> 00:27:02.000
it's roughly a third of this time.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:06.500
So if you're not doing the CSV parsing, it will get in faster.

00:27:06.500 --> 00:27:11.000
But I want to talk a little bit more about duckplyr.

00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:14.000
And while you read this, I'm going to have a sip of water.

00:27:15.000 --> 00:27:17.000
Hmm.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:23.000
So if we just run this on standard dplyr, this sequence of events,

00:27:23.000 --> 00:27:26.000
we're reading 35 million rows.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:30.000
This is what the data set contains, 35 million rows.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:34.000
And then we run this filter. Well, you can't really see it in the script,

00:27:34.000 --> 00:27:38.000
but the filter only matches to 14,000 rows,

00:27:38.000 --> 00:27:42.000
because that's just, you know, the way that the data is distributed.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:46.500
So we're throwing away all this other stuff except for these 14,000 rows.

00:27:46.500 --> 00:27:50.500
And then it's getting worse, because in the summarization,

00:27:50.500 --> 00:27:52.500
we only ever look at one of the columns.

00:27:52.500 --> 00:27:56.500
So we read the five other columns for no reason at all.

00:27:56.500 --> 00:27:59.500
And what we actually need to make this better is, as I mentioned,

00:27:59.500 --> 00:28:04.500
we need holistic optimization, where we can derive which columns are going to be used,

00:28:04.500 --> 00:28:07.500
which rows can be pruned earlier, and all these kind of things.

00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:16.000
But now we have this problem that if we now start making these data, data2, and results somehow lazy,

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:19.000
we would break the integration with other tools.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:22.000
Like, say we make this a lazy sort of placeholder object.

00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:25.000
We want to pass stuff into ggplot.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.000
ggplot would say, I don't know what this lazy thing is.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:34.000
So we somehow have to make the dplyr objects both data frames and lazy placeholders.

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:37.500
And we have thanks to this ALTREP framework, which is really exciting.

00:28:37.500 --> 00:28:42.500
In R, you can kind of make these objects that are sort of both things at the same time,

00:28:42.500 --> 00:28:45.500
and it can be both lazy and non-lazy at the same time.

00:28:45.500 --> 00:28:50.500
So if you use dplyr, these objects data2 and result will actually be data frames,

00:28:50.500 --> 00:28:55.500
and you can't really see a difference without...

00:28:55.500 --> 00:28:57.500
other tools cannot really see a difference,

00:28:57.500 --> 00:28:59.500
but we internally know that there are lazy representations,

00:28:59.500 --> 00:29:02.500
and we can do the holistic optimization.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:05.000
So this is really cool.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:08.000
If you want to try it out, it's on CRAN.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:12.000
There is a way of enabling telemetry if something goes wrong,

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:16.000
and I encourage you to do that if you want to help us improving dplyr duckplier.

00:29:16.000 --> 00:29:22.000
But we've also been super sensible in the sense that it will fall back to dplyr implementation

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
if there's something we don't understand in there,

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
so that you should actually not see a big difference when you just start using it.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:30.000
So I encourage you to do that.

00:29:30.000 --> 00:29:32.000
Okay, duckplier.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:35.000
I also want to show IBIS briefly,

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:38.000
because the cool thing about DuckDB is it's an engine

00:29:38.000 --> 00:29:42.000
that is kind of agnostic and multi-platform.

00:29:42.000 --> 00:29:46.000
So DuckDB also runs in Python,

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.000
and I don't know if Filip is here,

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.000
but he made this cool integration with IBIS

00:29:52.000 --> 00:29:57.000
that basically means you can write the same query again in IBIS syntax,

00:29:57.000 --> 00:30:00.000
which is this Python syntax that looks a bit like dplyr,

00:30:00.000 --> 00:30:03.000
and it will produce the exact same results,

00:30:03.000 --> 00:30:05.000
and it will also take, in this case, 1.3 seconds,

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:08.000
because it ends up also just being a DuckDB query plan.

00:30:08.000 --> 00:30:10.000
So it's really cool.

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:14.000
So now we've done complex queries with DuckDB,

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:18.000
and I've shown you that we can basically do very, very complicated questions

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:21.000
on fairly annoying datasets very quickly,

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:24.000
and we don't really have to fall back

00:30:24.000 --> 00:30:28.000
to my favorite programming language, SQL.

00:30:28.000 --> 00:30:31.000
Okay, but we've kind of...

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:34.000
So far this has been a bit of a defense, right?

00:30:34.000 --> 00:30:37.000
I've been defending against the accusation

00:30:37.000 --> 00:30:39.000
that databases are frustrating and slow.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:41.000
So I don't think DuckDB is frustrating and slow,

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:45.000
but the thing is that it's more to using data management systems

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:50.000
than, like, reading CSV files and running queries on them.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:54.000
And so I want to talk a bit about atomic datasets with DuckDB,

00:30:54.000 --> 00:30:56.000
and atomic is a positive thing.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:00.000
So just imagine it's the 50s, okay?

00:31:00.000 --> 00:31:04.000
Okay, so first of all,

00:31:04.000 --> 00:31:08.000
people say, yeah, okay, let's not use CSV.

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:10.000
And I agree. I'm a professor of data engineering.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.000
I agree. We should not use CSV files.

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.000
We should use Parquet files. That's true.

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:16.000
And DuckDB can actually help with this.

00:31:16.000 --> 00:31:18.000
In case you don't know what Parquet is,

00:31:18.000 --> 00:31:20.000
it's a parallel data format. It's really cool.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.000
DuckDB can read and write Parquet files very efficiently.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.000
So tip one, you should probably...

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.000
Step one before using DuckDB, consider using Parquet

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:29.000
if you don't fully trust me yet.

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:31.000
That one is a no-brainer.

00:31:31.000 --> 00:31:34.000
Yeah, and so we have native support for it in DuckDB.

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:37.000
There's other options, like Arrow has support for Parquet files

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.000
or the new Nano Parquet package from Posit.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.000
The interesting cool thing about Parquet file for this dataset

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:47.000
is actually that if you take this file,

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:49.000
which was an 800 megabyte CSV file,

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:51.000
if you turn it into a Parquet file,

00:31:51.000 --> 00:31:53.000
it's only 71 megabytes,

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:56.000
which is smaller than even the zip file that we had before.

00:31:56.000 --> 00:31:58.000
And it's actually much more efficient to read.

00:31:58.000 --> 00:32:00.000
So there's nothing not to like about it.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:02.000
But then what happens,

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:05.000
and I'm sure you've all seen this,

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.000
is like I've done a bunch of stuff in this folder

00:32:08.000 --> 00:32:10.000
with all these files. I've done some conversions.

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:13.000
I've done some scripting. I've done all these things.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
And now I end up with this ungodly mess of files, right?

00:32:16.000 --> 00:32:20.000
And there's no more sort of tracking

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:23.000
what came from where and what version was, you know,

00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:26.000
used to create this and what are these scripts doing.

00:32:26.000 --> 00:32:28.000
And some people use makefiles there.

00:32:28.000 --> 00:32:30.000
And then that makefile essentially interprets the files,

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:32.000
the timestamps there.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.000
But I don't think that's a great thing either.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:39.000
But we get this ungodly mess of all these files.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:42.000
And what we should be doing better,

00:32:42.000 --> 00:32:45.000
and actually DuckDB can help here

00:32:45.000 --> 00:32:48.000
because we can, in a DuckDB file,

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:50.000
we can store many tables.

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:53.000
We can store views. We can store functions.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:32:55.000
All of that in a single file.

00:32:55.000 --> 00:32:59.000
So what we can do is we can create here in this file,

00:32:59.000 --> 00:33:01.000
example, we can create a single DuckDB file

00:33:01.000 --> 00:33:05.000
that contains all the CSVs in parsed,

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:08.000
columnar, typed, compressed, binary formats.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
The ingestion can be atomic.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:13.000
So if I wrap this import statement there in a transaction,

00:33:13.000 --> 00:33:16.000
it either all goes through or nothing goes through.

00:33:16.000 --> 00:33:19.000
The resulting file is also around 100 megabytes.

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:22.000
So it's about the same as the zip file, just much better.

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:26.000
And we actually have, a couple of months ago,

00:33:26.000 --> 00:33:29.000
we have finalized our storage format.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.000
So this format is now, the DuckDB file format is now stable

00:33:32.000 --> 00:33:35.000
and will remain stable for the, you know, foreseeable future.

00:33:35.000 --> 00:33:38.000
And there's actually some organizations like Hugging Face

00:33:38.000 --> 00:33:41.000
that are already shipping all the data sets that they have,

00:33:41.000 --> 00:33:44.000
which is really crazy, as DuckDB files.

00:33:44.000 --> 00:33:46.000
So you go Hugging Face data set, you click a button

00:33:46.000 --> 00:33:49.000
and you get the DuckDB file. So it's really cool.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:52.000
They can even be read remotely via HTTP and S3.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:55.000
So it's really cool. So we put the data in this file.

00:33:55.000 --> 00:33:57.000
But that's not all.

00:33:57.000 --> 00:33:59.000
We can also do things like this,

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:01.000
where we can create something called views,

00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:03.000
which are like a sort of a virtual table

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:06.000
that you define a transformation using SQL

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:09.000
or you can also do this using some other tool,

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:11.000
but it doesn't really matter.

00:34:11.000 --> 00:34:13.000
And these views, they're actually stored in the file

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:15.000
and they travel with the file.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:17.000
And it makes it actually much easier

00:34:17.000 --> 00:34:19.000
to write high-level queries.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:22.000
And you can stack the views in order to sort of describe

00:34:22.000 --> 00:34:24.000
like multi-step derivations. And that means that

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:26.000
whenever you change something in the base table,

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:28.000
the views will actually update.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.000
They don't cost any storage because they are just

00:34:30.000 --> 00:34:33.000
sort of symbolic descriptions.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:36.000
And this hides, it's possible to hide a lot of complexity

00:34:36.000 --> 00:34:38.000
using this kind of tricks.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:40.000
And you can share the file with somebody else

00:34:40.000 --> 00:34:42.000
and they can look at the file and see the view

00:34:42.000 --> 00:34:45.000
and can directly use it. It's still a single file.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:34:50.000
Another thing that's really cool in DuckDB

00:34:50.000 --> 00:34:52.000
that you can create like macros,

00:34:52.000 --> 00:34:55.000
which are like sort of shortcuts into sort of things

00:34:55.000 --> 00:34:57.000
that you're using a lot. So on the top here,

00:34:57.000 --> 00:34:59.000
we're kind of repeating ourselves a lot

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:02.000
because they have used these total columns

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:04.000
in all these different dimensions there.

00:35:04.000 --> 00:35:06.000
And we kind of have to filter this out

00:35:06.000 --> 00:35:09.000
in order to not muck up our summaries.

00:35:09.000 --> 00:35:12.000
But you don't want to repeat

00:35:12.000 --> 00:35:14.000
like these ugly expressions 15 times.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.000
So you can create a macro and say,

00:35:16.000 --> 00:35:18.000
okay, I want to have a macro not total

00:35:18.000 --> 00:35:22.000
that has an arbitrary complex expression in it.

00:35:22.000 --> 00:35:24.000
They can just use it. And again,

00:35:24.000 --> 00:35:27.000
the cool thing is that macro will live in the file.

00:35:27.000 --> 00:35:29.000
So that means that you can send the file to somebody else

00:35:29.000 --> 00:35:31.000
and they can use it. It's really cool.

00:35:31.000 --> 00:35:33.000
And it's together with all the data, together with all the views,

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.000
together with everything.

00:35:35.000 --> 00:35:38.000
And finally,

00:35:38.000 --> 00:35:40.000
I want to talk about transactions.

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:42.000
I know that transactions are something

00:35:42.000 --> 00:35:45.000
that you may remember from a database course

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:47.000
where, you know, we move some money from A to B

00:35:47.000 --> 00:35:49.000
or something like that.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:35:51.000
But Mark has actually implemented

00:35:51.000 --> 00:35:54.000
the first really great transaction management

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.000
for analytical use cases

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:58.000
where we're changing data a lot,

00:35:58.000 --> 00:36:00.000
we're making, we're ingesting a lot of data,

00:36:00.000 --> 00:36:02.000
we're updating a lot of data, we're adding columns,

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:04.000
removing columns, that sort of stuff.

00:36:04.000 --> 00:36:06.000
And that means we can actually make these atomic,

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:08.000
this is why I said atomic,

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.000
atomic sort of sequences of changes to our data

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:13.000
that either all go through or not.

00:36:13.000 --> 00:36:16.000
And we can even do a manual rollback

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:19.000
if we did something by accident, if we didn't sort of intend.

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:21.000
So if I go back to this example here

00:36:21.000 --> 00:36:23.000
where, you know, I couldn't read the file

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:26.000
because it has some dot dot C in it,

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:28.000
you can just say, oh no, this was actually not what we want.

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:30.000
You can roll back and your file

00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:32.000
will be unaffected and the data

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
will be unaffected, okay?

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
There's a bunch of more stuff.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
These are just three examples I wanted to show

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
that data management systems actually have features

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:42.000
that go beyond what we're kind of used to,

00:36:42.000 --> 00:36:44.000
what we're using.

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:46.000
They go beyond what we're used to

00:36:46.000 --> 00:36:48.000
in like an analytical environment

00:36:48.000 --> 00:36:50.000
and they can actually be used for good.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Okay, so, um,

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
I will, uh,

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:56.000
I will respond

00:36:56.000 --> 00:36:58.000
to that.

00:36:58.000 --> 00:37:00.000
Just put your data inductively.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:02.000
Not doing so will only be slower

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
and more frustrating.

00:37:04.000 --> 00:37:06.000
Okay.

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:08.000
But now I have shown you what

00:37:08.000 --> 00:37:10.000
we can do

00:37:10.000 --> 00:37:12.000
with DuckDB and similar tools.

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:14.000
But I think it's an interesting question

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:16.000
and I would like to take the last couple of minutes

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:18.000
of the talk to actually discuss that.

00:37:18.000 --> 00:37:20.000
It's like, what does this actually mean

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.000
for data, for data engineering,

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:24.000
for data infrastructure?

00:37:24.000 --> 00:37:26.000
What does it mean if we have tools

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:28.000
that can actually, you know, comfortably

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:30.000
run through gigabytes of data on your laptop?

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:32.000
And there's been some discussion

00:37:32.000 --> 00:37:34.000
on this, uh,

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:36.000
whether big data is dead or not.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
And this is actually a case

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:40.000
where I use GenAI to, uh,

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:42.000
to create a picture

00:37:42.000 --> 00:37:44.000
and I quite like it.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:46.000
So, maybe it's a

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:48.000
overrated duck picture generator.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:50.000
But let me take you

00:37:50.000 --> 00:37:52.000
on a bit of a, um,

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
thought experiment, okay?

00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.000
So if we

00:37:56.000 --> 00:37:58.000
somehow, um, if we have,

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.000
if you say, let's just do

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:02.000
a thought experiment on data creation.

00:38:02.000 --> 00:38:04.000
The human typing speed

00:38:04.000 --> 00:38:06.000
is roughly 200 characters per minute.

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:08.000
The working population

00:38:08.000 --> 00:38:10.000
in the Netherlands is about

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:12.000
10 million people.

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:14.000
I will assume I have infinity money

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:16.000
because I've, you know, I'm a VC or something.

00:38:16.000 --> 00:38:18.000
And, um,

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:20.000
I've employed all of them.

00:38:20.000 --> 00:38:22.000
All 10 million.

00:38:22.000 --> 00:38:24.000
And the

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.000
work year of the Netherlands

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.000
has about 100,000 minutes,

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:30.000
give or take. So if I

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:32.000
employ the entire population

00:38:32.000 --> 00:38:34.000
for a whole year to type

00:38:34.000 --> 00:38:36.000
important data, I'm sure,

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:38.000
into a computer,

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:40.000
we will end up with roughly

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
200 terabytes of data.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
Well, this is, of course, ASCII text,

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.000
which is compressible, so if you

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:48.000
compress this somehow reasonably, we will end up

00:38:48.000 --> 00:38:50.000
with something like 60 terabytes.

00:38:50.000 --> 00:38:52.000
And that sounds like a lot, right?

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:54.000
60 terabytes.

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:56.000
But it's actually not.

00:38:56.000 --> 00:38:58.000
So you can buy these

00:38:58.000 --> 00:39:00.000
hard disks.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.000
They cost around $400.

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:04.000
There's a banana for scale.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:06.000
And...

00:39:06.000 --> 00:39:08.000
I mean, we have

00:39:08.000 --> 00:39:10.000
seen IBM hard disks from the 50s, right?

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:12.000
They were like these things that you lift into an airplane

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:14.000
and things like that. No, no, no, no. These are tiny.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:16.000
So the

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:18.000
maximum sort of

00:39:18.000 --> 00:39:20.000
output in usable data of the

00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.000
entire Netherlands working

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:24.000
population would easily fit

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:26.000
on these two hard disks.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:28.000
There's no scale-up required. I don't have to

