buy a Hadoop cluster for this.

00:39:30.000 --> 00:39:32.000
In two years,

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:34.000
it will be one disk.

00:39:34.000 --> 00:39:36.000
Will we have two times the amount of people

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:38.000
in the Netherlands? I sincerely doubt it.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:40.000
Okay? In ten

00:39:40.000 --> 00:39:42.000
years, this will fit on a laptop.

00:39:42.000 --> 00:39:44.000
The human

00:39:44.000 --> 00:39:46.000
growth in

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:48.000
people, and

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:50.000
people that can type anything or

00:39:50.000 --> 00:39:52.000
produce any meaningful data,

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:54.000
is growing much slower

00:39:54.000 --> 00:39:56.000
than our capabilities

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.000
in crunching through data. And I will

00:39:58.000 --> 00:40:00.000
go a bit more into that.

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
We look at compute.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:04.000
The Apple M3,

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:06.000
pretty standard computer, I'm sure some of you

00:40:06.000 --> 00:40:08.000
have one, has 16 cores.

00:40:08.000 --> 00:40:10.000
They are very

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.000
fast cores. They have 400 megabytes

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:14.000
of cache, which is totally insane,

00:40:14.000 --> 00:40:16.000
right? It's something that

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:18.000
these are the memory that the CPU

00:40:18.000 --> 00:40:20.000
can access in one or

00:40:20.000 --> 00:40:22.000
two cycles, right? It's insane

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:24.000
fast memory. They have 400 megabytes of it.

00:40:24.000 --> 00:40:26.000
I'm sure lots of data sets that you use

00:40:26.000 --> 00:40:28.000
every day are smaller than that. They can all be in the CPU

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
cache, no problem.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:32.000
This kind of performance is a hardcore

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:34.000
server machine from 2010.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.000
Again, I'm talking like big iron kind of

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:38.000
stuff.

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:40.000
These CPUs also have

00:40:40.000 --> 00:40:42.000
400 gigabytes per second

00:40:42.000 --> 00:40:44.000
in RAM throughput,

00:40:44.000 --> 00:40:46.000
and you can get these machines with hundreds of gigabytes

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:48.000
per RAM. The MacBook can have, I don't know,

00:40:48.000 --> 00:40:50.000
100-something gigabytes of RAM.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:52.000
So you have 400 gigabytes per second RAM

00:40:52.000 --> 00:40:54.000
throughput, and that's also completely

00:40:54.000 --> 00:40:56.000
insane in terms of performance, and we have

00:40:56.000 --> 00:40:58.000
kind of forgotten how fast this

00:40:58.000 --> 00:41:00.000
is going, and we're not realizing

00:41:00.000 --> 00:41:02.000
how much, like

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:04.000
how other data sets are growing in comparison.

00:41:04.000 --> 00:41:06.000
Similar for SSDs, right?

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:08.000
The SSDs are

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:10.000
a total game-changer for data processing because

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:12.000
of their speed. Current

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.000
MacBooks, again, 5.5 gigabytes

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:16.000
per second in I.O. from the

00:41:16.000 --> 00:41:18.000
SSD. It's insane.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:20.000
And with DuckDB, we can actually

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:22.000
take advantage of these

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:24.000
capabilities of the

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:26.000
hardware, for example

00:41:26.000 --> 00:41:28.000
in the SSD because, as I said, we can offload

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:30.000
intermediates to the SSD.

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:32.000
So you can go much larger than RAM

00:41:32.000 --> 00:41:34.000
with these things, and you won't really notice the

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:36.000
difference. But that's not...

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:38.000
Now we can go to bold prediction time. Fun stuff.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:40.000
So the data is growing.

00:41:40.000 --> 00:41:42.000
Yes.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:44.000
But it's probably slower than we

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:46.000
thought. There's a limited amount

00:41:46.000 --> 00:41:48.000
of people pushing buttons.

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:50.000
I think this is something that we sometimes

00:41:50.000 --> 00:41:52.000
don't realize.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.000
There's automatically

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:56.000
collected data, yes, but it tends to

00:41:56.000 --> 00:41:58.000
be less valuable, more repetitive.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:00.000
So here we just

00:42:00.000 --> 00:42:02.000
plot the useful data growth over time.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.000
And for the

00:42:04.000 --> 00:42:06.000
purpose of this argument, it actually doesn't matter whether the

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:08.000
axes are logarithmic or not.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:10.000
As we have seen,

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:12.000
the commodity compute

00:42:12.000 --> 00:42:14.000
hardware has been improving

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:16.000
like absolutely crazy in its

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:18.000
capabilities to crunch with data

00:42:18.000 --> 00:42:20.000
with the right software.

00:42:20.000 --> 00:42:22.000
And it's faster than the server hardware somehow

00:42:22.000 --> 00:42:24.000
now. It's really crazy.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:26.000
But we can

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:28.000
probably agree that single node

00:42:28.000 --> 00:42:30.000
capabilities grow faster

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.000
than the data sets are growing.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:36.000
In the past, there was a very large

00:42:36.000 --> 00:42:38.000
gap between what a single node

00:42:38.000 --> 00:42:40.000
could do, a single computer, a MacBook could do,

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:42.000
and sort of the

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:44.000
device, the 99%

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:46.000
percentile of size of data sets.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:48.000
So

00:42:48.000 --> 00:42:50.000
that meant that we had to go to distributed solutions

00:42:50.000 --> 00:42:52.000
very quickly, like

00:42:52.000 --> 00:42:54.000
big clusters of computers.

00:42:54.000 --> 00:42:56.000
Now it's less so, right? Now we

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:58.000
are much closer.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.000
And we're probably looking at the data singularity

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:02.000
at some point, where 99%

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:04.000
of data sets

00:43:04.000 --> 00:43:06.000
are actually comfortably

00:43:06.000 --> 00:43:08.000
processable

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:10.000
on a single computer.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.000
So this is really cool.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:14.000
It's really a fun

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:16.000
thought. And this is especially

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:18.000
important because research

00:43:18.000 --> 00:43:20.000
and a rant like this paper have

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:22.000
shown that going through distributed

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:24.000
environments is

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:26.000
increasing the cost

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:28.000
so massively that we actually

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:30.000
have to make huge clusters

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:32.000
in order to justify these costs.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:34.000
It's such a huge impact in terms

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:36.000
of cost and time that

00:43:36.000 --> 00:43:38.000
if you can run something on a single node,

00:43:38.000 --> 00:43:40.000
you probably should. And this was always

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:42.000
just a hunch, but I can

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:44.000
really recommend

00:43:44.000 --> 00:43:46.000
this blog post. It's called

00:43:46.000 --> 00:43:48.000
The Redshift Files, The Hunt

00:43:48.000 --> 00:43:50.000
for Big Data,

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:52.000
which is a blog post

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:54.000
that talks about a recent paper

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.000
from Amazon, who

00:43:56.000 --> 00:43:58.000
has for the first time actually confirmed this

00:43:58.000 --> 00:44:00.000
because they have published detailed

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:02.000
statistics and data

00:44:02.000 --> 00:44:04.000
about the data sets that they see

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:06.000
in their Redshift big data

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:08.000
processing system. And the answer

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:10.000
is, shockingly, that we're actually quite close

00:44:10.000 --> 00:44:12.000
to the singularity already.

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:14.000
The 99% of

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:16.000
data sets is actually something that does

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:18.000
now fit on a

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:20.000
small laptop. I'm going to do

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:22.000
one more round of experiments. I can't really

00:44:22.000 --> 00:44:24.000
do another talk here. As a database person,

00:44:24.000 --> 00:44:26.000
I feel very uncomfortable doing no benchmarks.

00:44:26.000 --> 00:44:28.000
So I'm doing one more experiment.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:30.000
So we're going to use

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:32.000
a data set from TPC. It's the standard

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:34.000
benchmark data set, TPC-H,

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:36.000
standard analytics benchmark data set.

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.000
And we're going to run Apache Spark

00:44:38.000 --> 00:44:40.000
versus DuckDB.

00:44:40.000 --> 00:44:42.000
Okay?

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:44.000
And we're going to run this on a fairly beefy Amazon

00:44:44.000 --> 00:44:46.000
box. I think it's like 32

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:48.000
nodes. Yeah, 32

00:44:48.000 --> 00:44:50.000
cores of CPU.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:52.000
Each node has 64 gigabytes

00:44:52.000 --> 00:44:54.000
of RAM. And we're running

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.000
scale factor 100, which is like a

00:44:56.000 --> 00:44:58.000
40 gigabyte data set. Not crazy, right?

00:44:58.000 --> 00:45:00.000
If we run this

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:02.000
on a single node...

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:04.000
Actually, we can't, because

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:06.000
Spark can't run on a single node.

00:45:06.000 --> 00:45:08.000
If you run this on a single node or two,

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:10.000
it will be seven times slower.

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:12.000
Why is that? Well,

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:14.000
it comes back to something I said before.

00:45:14.000 --> 00:45:16.000
First is the per-core performance

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:18.000
in Spark that's pretty problematic.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:20.000
And the other thing is this cost paper

00:45:20.000 --> 00:45:22.000
that I've also mentioned, that running

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:24.000
something in a distributed system is actually much more

00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:26.000
expensive than running it on a single node.

00:45:26.000 --> 00:45:28.000
So on a single node, this is slower.

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:30.000
But then you say, Hannes, you're being unfair.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.000
How can you dare comparing a

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:34.000
big data distributed system with your

00:45:34.000 --> 00:45:36.000
scrappy little database?

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:38.000
Okay. We scale up.

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:40.000
More computers.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:42.000
We're adding computers, and we're

00:45:42.000 --> 00:45:44.000
adding computers, and we're adding computers. And it turns out

00:45:44.000 --> 00:45:46.000
that even if we use 1,024 cores,

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:48.000
it will still be slower

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:50.000
than the single

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:52.000
node DuckDB instance.

00:45:52.000 --> 00:45:54.000
We're still paying for all these

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:56.000
1,024 cores here,

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.000
and we're still producing CO2.

00:45:58.000 --> 00:46:00.000
And one thing I think

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:02.000
that's worse, even, is that we have our high-paid

00:46:02.000 --> 00:46:04.000
analysts waiting for the

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:06.000
EMR cluster to come up, which I think

00:46:06.000 --> 00:46:08.000
is even more expensive than the actual compute

00:46:08.000 --> 00:46:10.000
here. And this never catches

00:46:10.000 --> 00:46:12.000
up because of this coordination

00:46:12.000 --> 00:46:14.000
cost in distributed systems.

00:46:14.000 --> 00:46:16.000
Okay.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:18.000
So that

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:20.000
was what I wanted to say. I have one more thing.

00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:22.000
And that is

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:24.000
I want to briefly talk about

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.000
DuckDB extensions.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:28.000
So we have realized

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:30.000
that we are clever people, but we cannot

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:32.000
really deal with everything.

00:46:32.000 --> 00:46:34.000
We don't understand everything.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:36.000
So we are actually opening up

00:46:36.000 --> 00:46:38.000
DuckDB for external

00:46:38.000 --> 00:46:40.000
extensions. Anyone.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:42.000
We call them community extensions.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:44.000
So you can expand DuckDB

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:46.000
with new functions, new formats, new

00:46:46.000 --> 00:46:48.000
syntax, new protocols, new compression

00:46:48.000 --> 00:46:50.000
— whatever you want.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.000
And this has so far been reserved

00:46:52.000 --> 00:46:54.000
to crazy people,

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:56.000
but we're now opening this up

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:58.000
to everyone. So all you do

00:46:58.000 --> 00:47:00.000
is you send us a pull request with your extension.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.000
It's like a descriptive file.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.000
And basically

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:06.000
you have a template for

00:47:06.000 --> 00:47:08.000
extensions that is a C++,

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:10.000
but we're working on

00:47:10.000 --> 00:47:12.000
extending this to Rust and other languages.

00:47:12.000 --> 00:47:14.000
And once you do that, you can actually

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:16.000
install these extensions

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.000
directly from within DuckDB

00:47:18.000 --> 00:47:20.000
and use them. And we think it's really going to be

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:22.000
the next big step

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:24.000
for us is to become an ecosystem

00:47:24.000 --> 00:47:26.000
of specific

00:47:26.000 --> 00:47:28.000
data transformation tools

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:30.000
that are connected with a high

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:32.000
fabric, a high-performance fabric

00:47:32.000 --> 00:47:34.000
that connects them together.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:36.000
This is kind of missing, I think, from the current

00:47:36.000 --> 00:47:38.000
analytics toolkits. It's like

00:47:38.000 --> 00:47:40.000
this idea that you can connect everything

00:47:40.000 --> 00:47:42.000
with consideration

00:47:42.000 --> 00:47:44.000
for parallelism and all that.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:46.000
And we're going to make this possible

00:47:46.000 --> 00:47:48.000
with these community extensions. And it's all going to be

00:47:48.000 --> 00:47:50.000
accessible for a single, sort of

00:47:50.000 --> 00:47:52.000
unified interface.

00:47:52.000 --> 00:47:54.000
So that's kind of it. In conclusion,

00:47:56.000 --> 00:47:58.000
databases are not frustrating

00:47:58.000 --> 00:48:00.000
and slow if their database is DuckDB.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:04.000
There's more cool database features

00:48:04.000 --> 00:48:06.000
beyond reading

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:08.000
CSV files and running SQL queries.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:10.000
I really think single node

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:12.000
is the future and that big data

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:14.000
is kind of dead. And actually, I'm quite

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:16.000
happy about this. And if you're still not done

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:18.000
with me,

00:48:18.000 --> 00:48:20.000
tomorrow afternoon, we're actually

00:48:20.000 --> 00:48:22.000
running DuckCon here in Seattle

00:48:22.000 --> 00:48:24.000
close by, and there's still some tickets

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:26.000
available, so it's free. If you want, you

00:48:26.000 --> 00:48:28.000
can go to our website and check that

00:48:28.000 --> 00:48:30.000
out. So with that, I thank you very much.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:32.000
Thank you.

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:42.000
Thanks, Hannes. Personally, I really enjoy

00:48:42.000 --> 00:48:44.000
it when a keynote speaker just destroys

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:46.000
something that I've said in the past.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:48.000
So we have

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:50.000
a few minutes for questions,

00:48:50.000 --> 00:48:52.000
so let's start.

00:48:52.000 --> 00:48:54.000
Since you can store all tables,

00:48:54.000 --> 00:48:56.000
views, and macros in a DuckDB

00:48:56.000 --> 00:48:58.000
file, how does a user explore

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
the file to see what's available? That's a great

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:02.000
question. So you can open up

00:49:02.000 --> 00:49:04.000
the file, and we have a command called show,

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:06.000
and it will show you what is

00:49:06.000 --> 00:49:08.000
in the file. So it will show you, oh, we have

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:10.000
these tables, we have these views. I don't think

00:49:10.000 --> 00:49:12.000
it necessarily lists the functions, but

00:49:12.000 --> 00:49:14.000
there's also ways of

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.000
exploring that. But you just type show.

00:49:18.000 --> 00:49:20.000
So you said DuckDB

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:22.000
is really an analytical database,

00:49:22.000 --> 00:49:24.000
but can you still kind of use

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:26.000
it in lightweight transactional content?

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:28.000
Like if you've got a Shiny app that's collecting a little

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.000
bit of data, how well

00:49:30.000 --> 00:49:32.000
does that work? Yeah, I think

00:49:32.000 --> 00:49:34.000
what you shouldn't be doing is make a loop

00:49:34.000 --> 00:49:36.000
with a thousand iterations, and every

00:49:36.000 --> 00:49:38.000
iteration of that loop inserts a single

00:49:38.000 --> 00:49:40.000
row and then commits. Don't

00:49:40.000 --> 00:49:42.000
do that.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
But if you want to, you know, do

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
a couple of hundred thousand,

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:48.000
a few changes,

00:49:48.000 --> 00:49:50.000
that's not an issue, right?

00:49:50.000 --> 00:49:52.000
You can definitely commit a single row,

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:54.000
no problem. It's just not going to be

00:49:54.000 --> 00:49:56.000
competitive, let's say, with Postgres.

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.000
I will say I have

00:49:58.000 --> 00:50:00.000
a Shiny app

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.000
that generates Madlib

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:04.000
stories.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:06.000
I don't know if you know what a Madlib is.

00:50:06.000 --> 00:50:08.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:10.000
And it logs every Madlib to

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:12.000
Mother Duck using DuckDB,

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:14.000
which kind of works

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:16.000
amazingly well.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:18.000
I always love,

00:50:18.000 --> 00:50:20.000
one of my other favorite examples is in

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:22.000
Big R Query, which works with Google's

00:50:22.000 --> 00:50:24.000
Big Query. It uses empty cars

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.000
as this test data set. I just love the

00:50:26.000 --> 00:50:28.000
thought of using these massive

00:50:28.000 --> 00:50:30.000
data sets that can deal with gigabytes of

00:50:30.000 --> 00:50:32.000
data and just sending it 30

00:50:32.000 --> 00:50:34.000
rows of data at a time. They love you too at

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:36.000
Google, I'm sure.

00:50:38.000 --> 00:50:40.000
Why did you name it DuckDB?

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:42.000
Ah, it's a great question.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:44.000
Why is it called DuckDB?

00:50:44.000 --> 00:50:46.000
So, I live on a boat

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:48.000
and I

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:50.000
wanted a pet.

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:52.000
Boats are kind of dangerous for pets,

00:50:52.000 --> 00:50:54.000
so I figured I'm going to have a pet

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:56.000
that can swim.

00:50:56.000 --> 00:50:58.000
So, I

00:50:58.000 --> 00:51:00.000
ended up having a duck called Wilbur.

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:02.000
Wilbur at some point grew up and went away.

00:51:02.000 --> 00:51:04.000
But DuckDB

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:06.000
is named in his honor.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:08.000
Not to name drop, but I actually

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:10.000
met Wilbur. You have met Wilbur!

00:51:12.000 --> 00:51:14.000
It's true.

00:51:14.000 --> 00:51:16.000
Help me,

00:51:16.000 --> 00:51:18.000
I am lost. If I load my big

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:20.000
CSV into R, it crashes.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.000
Would this be different using

00:51:22.000 --> 00:51:24.000
DuckDB? Yes.

00:51:24.000 --> 00:51:26.000
The reason why it crashes

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:28.000
is because when you load

00:51:28.000 --> 00:51:30.000
a CSV file into R, it will have

00:51:30.000 --> 00:51:32.000
to go into memory.

00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.000
If your big CSV file is bigger than memory,

00:51:34.000 --> 00:51:36.000
at some point the operating system

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:38.000
will say, you process,

00:51:38.000 --> 00:51:40.000
we're out of memory, you die now.

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:44.000
In DuckDB

00:51:44.000 --> 00:51:46.000
we can use memory to store data,

00:51:46.000 --> 00:51:48.000
but we can also use the disk.

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:50.000
What you can do

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:52.000
is load DuckDB up, and we can

00:51:52.000 --> 00:51:54.000
connect to a file on disk

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.000
and move the file there, and then we'll never

00:51:56.000 --> 00:51:58.000
materialize this file in memory entirely.

00:51:58.000 --> 00:52:00.000
That's, I think, one of the really

00:52:00.000 --> 00:52:02.000
cool features, that you can go larger than

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:04.000
memory in datasets because you never

00:52:04.000 --> 00:52:06.000
materialize this file in memory. That even applies

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:08.000
to intermediates, which is really important.

00:52:08.000 --> 00:52:10.000
I had this example earlier when I said

00:52:10.000 --> 00:52:12.000
what if you sort your

00:52:12.000 --> 00:52:14.000
terabyte file?

00:52:14.000 --> 00:52:16.000
Traditionally, that has to go into memory to be

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:18.000
sorted, and then it would crash because we don't have

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:20.000
a terabyte of memory, but we have made

00:52:20.000 --> 00:52:22.000
a very clever sorting algorithm

00:52:22.000 --> 00:52:24.000
that can use the disk and offload

00:52:24.000 --> 00:52:26.000
efficiently, and then it will

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:28.000
work.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:34.000
How well does DuckDB scale up to

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:36.000
really big and complex database

00:52:36.000 --> 00:52:38.000
systems, so hundreds or thousands

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:40.000
of users loading and retrieving data,

00:52:40.000 --> 00:52:42.000
hundreds of tables, user

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:44.000
indication?

00:52:44.000 --> 00:52:46.000
That's a great question.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:48.000
If thousands

00:52:48.000 --> 00:52:50.000
of users at the same time is not really something that

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:52.000
DuckDB is made for. It was made to support

00:52:52.000 --> 00:52:54.000
in one way

00:52:54.000 --> 00:52:56.000
the analytics use case, and the other way

00:52:56.000 --> 00:52:58.000
a data transformation pipeline use

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:00.000
case. If you're

00:53:00.000 --> 00:53:02.000
trying to run with thousands

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:04.000
of users, it's

00:53:04.000 --> 00:53:06.000
probably not the tool for you.

00:53:06.000 --> 00:53:08.000
Hundreds of tables is not a problem. Hundreds

00:53:08.000 --> 00:53:10.000
of columns, thousands of columns is not an issue.

00:53:10.000 --> 00:53:12.000
Complexity of queries is not an issue,

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:14.000
but the concurrent use by

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.000
thousands of users is still

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.000
something that's not really the design

00:53:18.000 --> 00:53:20.000
goal, let's say. But I can

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:22.000
plug MotherDuck here, so it's kind of what they do.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:26.000
Kind of a related note, how does DuckDB

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:28.000
handle read and write concurrency?

00:53:28.000 --> 00:53:30.000
Yeah, read and write

00:53:30.000 --> 00:53:32.000
concurrency, so we

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:34.000
use MVCC, multi-version currency

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:36.000
control, which basically means that a query will

00:53:36.000 --> 00:53:38.000
see a consistent local state,

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:40.000
and then when we commit,

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:42.000
we have to check whether there have been

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:44.000
any conflicts, and

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:46.000
that happens automatically in the background.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:48.000
So basically, you

00:53:48.000 --> 00:53:50.000
can have many, many threads at the same time

00:53:50.000 --> 00:53:52.000
reading and writing to the database,

00:53:52.000 --> 00:53:54.000
and there is an automated check

00:53:54.000 --> 00:53:56.000
that sees if there's any sort of

00:53:56.000 --> 00:53:58.000
conflicts that have to be resolved

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:00.000
or cannot be resolved. But in principle

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:02.000
that works fine.

00:54:02.000 --> 00:54:04.000
Cool. Does DuckDB

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:06.000
work well reading and writing data

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:08.000
and cloud object storage, like AWS

00:54:08.000 --> 00:54:10.000
CS3, Azure, Bobstor, etc.?

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:12.000
Yes.

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:14.000
That was an easy one.

00:54:14.000 --> 00:54:16.000
Yes, it does.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:18.000
At my workplace, CSV is the default data

00:54:18.000 --> 00:54:20.000
format for data sharing. Is now the time

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:22.000
to switch to Parquet? Yes.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:26.000
I mean, yes.

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:28.000
I think that the time was five years ago, but...

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:32.000
Let's see if I can give you any more easy questions.

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
Here's a tough one.

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:36.000
Are there any downsides to using DuckDB

00:54:36.000 --> 00:54:38.000
you can think of for data analysis,

00:54:38.000 --> 00:54:40.000
either for interactive work or production apps?

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:42.000
I think the kickbacks from your Oracle rep

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:44.000
will be less.

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:46.000
Downsides...

00:54:46.000 --> 00:54:48.000
I mean, I'm the wrong person to ask about this.

00:54:48.000 --> 00:54:50.000
I think what we really...

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:52.000
We see a lot of feedback from users

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:54.000
on GitHub, right? We see a lot of issues.

00:54:54.000 --> 00:54:56.000
Not that many, but we see issues reported.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:54:58.000
We have discussions.

00:54:58.000 --> 00:55:00.000
There is design choices that

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:02.000
work for some people and don't work

00:55:02.000 --> 00:55:04.000
for other people.

00:55:04.000 --> 00:55:06.000
Are there any downsides of using DuckDB?

00:55:06.000 --> 00:55:08.000
I think there are definitely use cases

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:10.000
that it wasn't made for.

00:55:12.000 --> 00:55:14.000
Like you said earlier,

00:55:14.000 --> 00:55:16.000
if you're suddenly going to

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:18.000
use it for a transactional use case,

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:20.000
it's not the tool for the job.

00:55:20.000 --> 00:55:22.000
It's an analytical system.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
If you were to force it to do that,

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:26.000
that would be not great.

00:55:26.000 --> 00:55:28.000
Any downsides?

00:55:28.000 --> 00:55:30.000
I'm really not the person

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:32.000
to ask for this, I think.

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:34.000
So, no downsides.

00:55:34.000 --> 00:55:36.000
Ask somebody else.

00:55:36.000 --> 00:55:38.000
Thanks so much.

00:55:38.000 --> 00:55:40.000
Thank you.

